metadata.name: Reisiger #425
metadata.description:
We journey through the world, collecting ideas, friendships, loves and experiences. This journey is life and, if you're fortunate, the majority of your journey is good and you eventually meet your Gods knowing that you've lived well.

Reisiger means Traveler in Afrikaans, and this work is meant to portray the hope, joy and diversity of our travail through life.

This piece assembles a simple mesh along a bezier spline of an orbital path around a series of bodies. It uses Newtonian gravity - adequately mangled to make it more interesting - and applies a number of transformations in flight. Hatching and occlusion algorithms are custom, but are developed based on work by Reinder Nijhoff. 

This is a plotter artwork and is intended to be enjoyed both on screen and in print. When printing, choose your pens appropriately - gel pens for dark paper etc, all colours are meant as a suggestion and all versions should look just fine in monochrome if you so choose. If you want an upscaled raster artwork (for regular printing) just add a dpr param to the URL like &dpr=10.

Left-click to download a PNG.
Double-click to download an SVG file ready for plotting.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: Spirali #49
metadata.description:
INSPIRATION

Spirali was inspired by Tyler Hobbs' work with flow fields. However, instead of selecting random starting points for each shape to be drawn, which is more usual in flow fields works, I wanted to constrain the starting points to certain positions so that the shape being drawn could expand freely without the risk of colliding with other shapes, that's when I got to the spiral flow field.

WHY SPIRALI?

The name of this collection is not only a direct translation of spirals in Italian, but it is also related to Italian cuisine and my own personal experience in Italy. The relationship with Italian cuisine is due to the immense number of types of pasta that exist, including one called spirali. When I was a child I only knew three or four types of pasta, but when I became a bit older I was amazed to learn that there were many more. Actually, there are hundreds. Just like from the same type of basic dough, you can make hundreds of types of pasta, my idea was, from just one type of spiral flow field, to make hundreds of images. A strategy of forcing creativity by imposing a major constraint.

The name of this collection also relates to my personal experience because it was visiting Italy many years ago that I first became interested in art and design because of the beautiful buildings, churches and works of art that I came across.

DESIGN STRATEGY

A spirali is made up of several tails and each tail is made up of a basic element, which I called slice. A tail may have from one to thousands slices. It is mainly the variation in the number of slices and how they are colored that creates the different tail styles in each spirali.

The slices start at the center of the spiral and in each iteration they grow a certain length or split in two depending on the parameters used in the algorithm, which also determine the outline and fill of each slice when it is rendered.

FEATURES

The main features that a spirali can have are:

- Styles: Refers to the drawing patterns of each tail, that means, the shape, fill and stroke of the slices that form the tail. There are about 16 possible styles from which the algorithm will choose about 3 for each spirali.

- Zoom out: It is related to how much larger the flow field area is in comparison to the image area. There are two possibilities: 50% and 100%.

- Curvature: An arbitrary measure of the rate the tails of a spirali are turning. A spirali can have high or low curvature.

- Rotation: The rotation direction: clockwise or counterclockwise.

- Tails: The number of tails in a spirali.

- Palette: The palette's name. There are about 14 possible palettes.

COMMANDS:

- Press "m" to export a medium resolution image (2000px x 2000px);
- Press "h" to export a high resolution image (6000px x 6000px);

LICENSING

Please see license.txt file.

Twitter: @PauloSilvaGArt
Site: https://paulosilva.art

metadata.name: Original Threads  #66
metadata.description:
Original Threads is an exploration of the winding of digital thread. Originally developed as an experiment of recreating rolls of thread in p5js, this collaboration of efforts combines se.nao.neste's core algorithmic work with Liam's drive to push as much coherent variety into a generator as possible.

At its core, this work wraps threads around a central point, subscribing to various rules as it does so. The movement of the thread is determined by the angular momentum combined with a "wander" factor.

One of the most exciting parts of the development of this algorithm was discovering and exploiting the various idiosyncracies (the peculiarities) of the drawing algorithm - the broken lines when the stroke is above a certain weight, the "burning" of the heavily layered shadows etc. - these "mistakes" we've loved and cherished and became an intrinsic part of the artistic expression of the piece.

Double-tap / hit "s" to download an image.
Add a URL parameter of "dpr" (for example ?dpr=4) to increse the resolution.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details

metadata.name: Ataraxis #431
metadata.description:
Ataraxis (or a broken volume renderer) is an exploration in balancing discomfort and calm. The piece generates spaces on the fly that are designed to elicit strange and uncomfortable feelings - like a desolate, alien dreamscape - claustrophobic, surreal, not quite real yet strangely recognisable. But the idea is that while these spaces feel uncomfortable, they're also strangely, antilogically calming. The idea is to elicit a sanguine emotion, to make the viewer feel calm in a strange place, and to lead them somewhere else.

This work is the culmination of many years of work researching volumetric rendering techniques. This token uses a raymarching technique that is intentionally broken in various ways.

Controls:
Double-click to download
&w=X&h=y to change the size of the piece
&dpr=x to change the resolution of the pice - higher resolutions will result in slightly different artworks as the browser attempts to compensate for the overlarge canvas
&fullscreen=true to change the token to display the full size of your browser. This may impact the rendering of the token, so use with caution

metadata.name: Digital Surrogates #16
metadata.description:
“Allan McCollum’s Plaster Surrogates was a thought-provoking series of sculptures that examines the role of art in contemporary society. The sculptures are cast from plaster and painted to resemble frames, mats, and black rectangles, creating a visual illusion of empty picture frames. McCollum's intention with the surrogates was to comment on the mass production and consumption of art objects, as well as the way in which art is often valued for its social function rather than its inherent aesthetic qualities.”

Continuing the integration of generative art and conceptual art, this work is a digital reproduction and inspiration of Plaster Surrogates - 1982 by noted conceptual artist, Allan McCollum.

Even though the original work had completely black rectangles, in this work, contrasting colors are used in some variations to increase the beauty. The dimensions and colors of the frames are calculated according to McCollum's original work. Various color palettes and canvas sizes have been used.

-----------

No images are used, created entirely by coding. Textures such as wood, canvas, and oil paint have been created to create a realistic look. Preview optimized for fxhash capturing system and full rendering can take up to several minutes, so I highly recommend checking out this artwork in high quality.


To save the artwork in high resolution, Open it in the live mode, it will be saved automatically after completion.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Symbolic Separations #44
metadata.description:
Is this a metaphor for the unstable process of division? Or colours and shapes morphing and inverting along imaginary, fluxing and blurred boundaries?

At least we know it's two passes through two different GLSL shaders, where waves are blurred, turbulence accumulated, and lines drawn to flip colors.

## Controls

Press [spacebar] to toggle play/pause.

When paused, press the keys [1] through [4] to change the resolution.

[1] - 2400px x 2400px

[2] - 3600px x 3600px

[3] - 4800px x 4800px

[4] - 5400px x 5400px

Then (also only when paused) press [p] to create a hi-res PNG.
